The graph looks different because removing the "index" column changed the scale of the y-axis.

Why?
Previous Graph:

The "index" column had a large range, which stretched the y-axis.
This made other boxplots look compressed.
Current Graph (After Removing "index"):

The y-axis is now rescaled based on the highest numerical values among the remaining columns.
The other boxplots have more visible details now.

Note:- The boxplot itself hasnt changedthe data is the same. Only the y-axis scale has adjusted, 
making the outliers and distributions clearer.
"""

#Now we are detecting the exact number of outliers from the boxplot with the help of interquartile range

# Define a function to detect outliers using IQR
def detect_outliers_iqr(df, column):
    Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    return df[(df[column] < lower_bound) | (df[column] > upper_bound)]

# Check outliers for each numerical column
numeric_cols = df1.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns
outliers = {col: detect_outliers_iqr(df1, col) for col in numeric_cols}

# Print the number of outliers in each column
for col, outlier_df in outliers.items():
    print(f"{col}: {len(outlier_df)} outliers")

#detecting outliers using z-score
from scipy import stats

# Define a function to detect outliers using Z-score
def detect_outliers_zscore(df, column, threshold=3):
    z_scores = np.abs(stats.zscore(df[column]))
    return df[z_scores > threshold]

# Check outliers for each numerical column
outliers_zscore = {col: detect_outliers_zscore(df1, col) for col in numeric_cols}

# Print the number of outliers in each column
for col, outlier_df in outliers_zscore.items():
    print(f"{col}: {len(outlier_df)} outliers using Z-score")

#applying log transformation to normalize the graph or to reduce the outliers

columns_to_transform = ['Unit Cost', 'Unit Price', 'Cost', 'Revenue']

# Apply log transformation (adding 1 to avoid log(0))
for col in columns_to_transform:
    df1[col + '_log'] = np.log1p(df1[col])

# Plot before and after log transformation
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, len(columns_to_transform), figsize=(15, 6))

for i, col in enumerate(columns_to_transform):
    # Before log transformation
    sns.kdeplot(df1[col], shade=True, ax=axes[0, i])
    axes[0, i].set_title(f"Before Log: {col}")

    # After log transformation
    sns.kdeplot(df1[col + '_log'], shade=True, ax=axes[1, i])
    axes[1, i].set_title(f"After Log: {col}")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

def remove_outliers_iqr(df, column):
    Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    return df[(df[column] >= lower_bound) & (df[column] <= upper_bound)]

# Apply to each column
df_no_outliers = df1.copy()

#as we saw the previous graphs for before and after log transformation, now we will check for the values that
#are outliers and how many number of outliers

# Function to detect outliers using IQR
def detect_outliers_iqr(df, column):
    Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    outliers = df[(df[column] < lower_bound) | (df[column] > upper_bound)]
    return outliers, len(outliers)

# List of log-transformed columns
log_columns = ['Unit Cost_log', 'Unit Price_log', 'Cost_log', 'Revenue_log']

# Check for outliers
for col in log_columns:
    outliers, count = detect_outliers_iqr(df1, col)
    print(f"Outliers in {col}: {count}")
    if count > 0:
        print(f"Outlier values: \n{outliers[[col]]}\n")

# Assuming df1 is your dataframe with log-transformed data
columns = ['Unit Cost_log', 'Unit Price_log', 'Cost_log', 'Revenue_log']

# Detect outliers using IQR method
outliers_after_log = pd.DataFrame()

for col in columns:
    Q1 = df1[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df1[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    outliers_col = df1[(df1[col] < (Q1 - 1.5 * IQR)) | (df1[col] > (Q3 + 1.5 * IQR))]
    outliers_after_log = pd.concat([outliers_after_log, outliers_col])

# Plotting boxplots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))
for i, col in enumerate(columns):
    sns.boxplot(y=df1[col], ax=axes[i//2, i%2])
    axes[i//2, i%2].set_title(f'Boxplot of {col}')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Plotting scatter plots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))
for i, col in enumerate(columns):
    sns.scatterplot(x=df1.index, y=df1[col], ax=axes[i//2, i%2], color='blue', label='Data')
    if col in outliers_after_log.columns:
        sns.scatterplot(x=outliers_after_log.index, y=outliers_after_log[col], ax=axes[i//2, i%2], color='red', label='Outliers')
    axes[i//2, i%2].set_title(f'Scatter Plot of {col}')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.legend()
